{"key":"processedPost-13251781","value":{"id":13251781,"first":13250768,"last":13251781,"when":1285564086,"utime":"09/27/10 08:08 AM","content":"You're correct about too wet or too dry ruining performance.<br />Cakes made a bit on the dry side will colonize faster, but will need extra water to fruit properly.&nbsp; Cakes made on the 'slightly' wet side will colonize slower, but usually have enough moisture for first flush.<br />The best of both worlds is to make the cakes slightly dry, and then soak for 12 to 24 hours before first flush, otherwise known as dunk and roll.<br />By using a ratio of one part brown rice flour or rice bran, one part water and two parts fine vermiculite, your mix will be slightly dry.&nbsp; I'd suggest this mix.&nbsp; If you're using course or medium vermiculite, you might need to use a bit more to keep the mix from being too wet.&nbsp; I'd suggest following the procedure shown in the <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/BRF-Pf-Tek\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">brf tek video</a>.&nbsp; Note the consistency of the mix, and try to duplicate that.&nbsp; It's perfect.<br />RR","title":"Re: Cakes and Moisture"}}